.TH _PRINTF 3 "Nov 2025" "v1.0" "Library Functions"
.SH NAME
_printf \- custom formatted output function
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.br
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function writes output to the standard output stream (stdout) under the
control of a format string. The
.B format
string is a null-terminated C string containing ordinary characters and
conversion specifiers. Additional arguments must follow the format string,
corresponding to the conversion specifiers encountered.

This implementation supports the following conversion specifiers:

.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.

.TP
.B %s
Prints a null-terminated string.

.TP
.B %d, %i
Prints a signed decimal integer.

.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal '%' character.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success, the function returns the total number of characters printed.
If an error occurs, or if the function receives an invalid format string,
it returns -1.

.SH ERRORS
The behaviour is undefined if:
.IP \[bu]
The number or types of arguments do not match the format specifiers.
.IP \[bu]
The
.B format
string is NULL.

.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
#include "main.h"

int main(void)
{
    _printf("Hello, world!\\n");
    _printf("Character: %c, String: %s, Number: %d, Percent: %%\\n",
            'A', "Test", 42);
    return (0);
}
.fi

.SH AUTHOR
Leny Blee and Ethane Zimmermann

.SH SEE ALSO
printf(3)
